"What is the value of a child's life?" 

@blakelively said it best: The sexual abuse and exploitation of children isn't a problem happening rarely or worlds away. It's happening right here, right now, in OUR neighborhoods.

That's why the proactive work we're doing at Child Rescue Coalition, in partnership with law enforcement agencies across the globe is so vital.

Get involved or make a donation today at the link in bio.

node.text:
Research shows that by the age of 2, 90 percent of children already have a presence on social media.

Help protect your child’s privacy and ensure their image doesn’t fall into the hands of predators. Before sharing your child’s image on social media, ask yourself:

Why am I sharing this?

Would I want someone else to share an image like this of me?

Would I want this image of my child viewed and downloaded by predators on the Dark Web?

Is this something I want to be part of my child’s digital life?

Once you’ve posted your child’s photo, you can’t have total control over it, so think twice about sharing something that may seem cute or innocent. 

Together, we can bring safety to our children and other victims of child sexual abuse around the world.

Each of these dots represents at least one predator that is online RIGHT NOW trading child sexual abuse material. Alarming, right?

Our CRC Technology provides the most comprehensive view of where child predators around the world are downloading and sharing explicit content online. We provide our data to law enforcement agencies in 97 countries free of charge to help them protect children by tracking, arresting and prosecuting child predators worldwide — often without having to put children through the trauma of testifying in court.

By commenting on and sharing our social media posts, attending events, and donating, you become partners with us in raising awareness for this horrific issue and allow us to keep this technology FREE.

Learn more at the link in bio.

Child Rescue Coalition is proud to have collaborated with the UK Border Force to produce this awareness raising video from the perspective of a parent. This is based on a real case and is the second in a series of three.

Parents everywhere are struggling to keep up with technology. Knowing what makes an online game or app dangerous allows parents to identify the dangers and to empower their children to protect themselves in the online environment.

This parent's child became the victim of an online predator, please make sure your family is not the next one to suffer from this horrific abuse.

This resource is available in 10 native languages, is presented by Child Rescue Coalition and made possible through the support of the UK Home Office. We are grateful for your support in spreading this message to protect children across the globe.

node.text:
We are proud to release this awareness video from the perspective of law enforcement officers, it is the first in a series of three. Officers do an incredibly difficult job helping to protect children from dangerous pedophiles. An offender may have known their victim for many years, or could be causing the abuse from thousands of miles away.

No one organization can tackle this problem, but by sharing what they've learned and working together - we can ALL make a difference. It takes a network to defeat a network, and we all need to join the fight to prevent this abuse from happening.

This resource is available in 10 native languages, and is presented by Child Rescue Coalition, and made possible through the support of the UK Home Office. We are grateful for your support in spreading this message to protect kids across the globe.

node.text:
When Jeremy turned 24, his life began to change. He started having severe bouts of sadness. These episodes started lasting hours, and they came coupled with memories of when he was a young 8-year-old boy and was abused. He had decided to fight the memories, but that wasn't working only making things worse.

He knew he needed to do something about it, so he searched for an outlet to express what had happened to him. He started using open mics as a way of sharing his story to encourage others but the audience there was not right for his platform and he would at times get harassed.

He thought he couldn’t take one more night, but knew the best option was to keep going. He started getting creative with how he told his story and it was catching people’s attention. And with this, he knew he was on to something. Jeremy has now been speaking out in public for two years.

He, like us, believes that we must bring more attention to this subject, which is essential if we stand any chance of breaking the stigma and the silence. Let's encourage others to #jointhefigt and speak out because that's the first step into making a change.

Written by: @jeremyindika 
Animation by: @kingbeeanimation 
Sound Design: @leemas9

.
The support we have received over the past 7 years has been tremendous, thank you for helping us rescue children from sexual abuse. But there is still so much more we can do.
.

As a nonprofit, our mission is made possible through the generous support of individuals and from partnerships with private corporations. This allows us to integrate our CRC Technology into law enforcement agencies in all 50 U.S. States and 97 countries for FREE. Our technology has been pivotal in identifying and indexing millions of IP addresses linked to the sharing of child sexual abuse material.

And remember, these predators can be harming children all over the globe, no matter where they live. That's why it's so important to keep training law enforcement worldwide.

Child Rescue Coalition was founded by sisters Carly and Desiree, who took the technology their father invented and turned it into a nonprofit organization currently operating in 97 countries worldwide!

I am proud to recognize her on sister’s day because so much of what we have been able to do at CRC was possible because of her!" - Carly Yoost, CEO and Co-Founder of Child Rescue Coalition

"What is the value of a child's life?" 

@blakelively said it best: The sexual abuse and exploitation of children isn't a problem happening rarely or worlds away. It's happening right here, right now, in OUR neighborhoods.

That's why the proactive work we're doing at Child Rescue Coalition, in partnership with law enforcement agencies across the globe is so vital.

Get involved or make a donation today at the link in bio.

node.text:
It’s World Day Against Trafficking in Persons. 

 Have you heard the terms “Live Streaming Abuse” or “Online Child Sexual Exploitation”?

What these terms really describe is the trafficking of children for payment online. Our work with law enforcement tells us that, at least, tens of thousands of pedophiles are actively engaged in paying money to view the sexual abuse of children live online. 

This heinous crime must be tackled from both the buyer and trafficker side of the transaction. At Child Rescue Coalition, we are working directly with investigators who are dealing with this crime type on a daily basis. 

Read more from the blog “Live Streaming Abuse: Where Human Trafficking Meets Child Exploitation” at the link in bio.

node.text:
"It troubled me how and where something like this could have happened. I had always been careful with play dates, and Amelia did not like sleepovers. In addition, my heart sank as I realised that regardless of my vigilance, I had been unable to protect my child.

The next day, I called the police and asked them if they publish on their webpage a list of games that predators were known to frequent. They responded with, 'No  — predators are on all the games.'"

Read more of Amelia's story and get more safety and parenting tips on our blog at the link in bio.

Troian Bellisario, Actress/ Activist CHiLD RESCUE COALITION'.

node.text:
Troian Bellisario is an actress, two time Teen Choice Award winner, wife, and mama of two. She's also an advocate and supporter of Child Rescue Coalition.

“Child consent over their own image is a really important topic to me. Once an image is taken of a child -- which I might view one way as a mother -- if put online... I have no control over where the world might take that."

Hear more about why Troian supports CRC on IGTV where she talked candidly with CRC Founder and CEO @carlyyoostcrc.

Thank you @sleepinthegardn for supporting our mission to protect innocence through technology.

node.text:
For less than the cost of a drive-thru coffee a week, you could help make a real difference in the fight to save children from sexual abuse.

The data shows that 1 in 10 children will be sexually abused before their 18th birthday. This isn't a far away problem -- it's happening to children right now, as you're reading this post.

Become a Coalition Club member for just $25/month and help us continue to rescue kids and prevent abuse by finding the people who prey on them.

node.text:
Current CRC technology users from Paraguay, Panama, Colombia, Costa Rica and Ecuador joined their Dominican Republic colleagues to be trained as Instructors.

This accreditation enables them to return to their home countries and in turn train more law enforcement officers to track and arrest those with an illegal sexual interest in children.

We are so humbled and appreciative of the support of First Lady, Raquel Arbaje, who is helping to give a voice to those who can’t speak for themselves.

Research shows that by the age of 2, 90 percent of children already have a presence on social media.

Help protect your child’s privacy and ensure their image doesn’t fall into the hands of predators. Before sharing your child’s image on social media, ask yourself:

Why am I sharing this?

Would I want someone else to share an image like this of me?

Would I want this image of my child viewed and downloaded by predators on the Dark Web?

Is this something I want to be part of my child’s digital life?

Once you’ve posted your child’s photo, you can’t have total control over it, so think twice about sharing something that may seem cute or innocent. 

Together, we can bring safety to our children and other victims of child sexual abuse around the world.

TikTok has roughly 1 billion active monthly users. Over 32% of those users are 10-19 years old.

While TikTok can be a great way for kids to connect with friends and have fun, like any social media platform targeted at young people, it also comes with potential dangers. Use these six tips to help keep your child safe on TikTok.

We provide our data to law enforcement agencies in 97 countries free of charge to help them protect children by tracking, arresting and prosecuting child predators worldwide — often without having to put children through the trauma of testifying in court.

By commenting on and sharing our social media posts, attending events, and donating, you become partners with us in raising awareness for this horrific issue and allow us to keep this technology FREE.
